PERFORMANCE WORK STATEMENT
Department of the Army – Program Executive Office Enterprise Information Systems (PEO EIS)
Contract No. W52P1J-25-D-0038

PWS 3.2 ENTERPRISE IT SERVICE MANAGEMENT SUPPORT

The Contractor shall deliver end-to-end IT service management support for the Army's Integrated Personnel and Pay System (IPPS-A) sustainment environment. The Contractor's team shall consist of no fewer than 22 FTEs organized across the following functional areas:

(a) Service Delivery Management: Program Manager, Deputy Program Manager, Transition Manager, and Integrated Master Schedule Analyst (4 FTEs);
(b) Application Sustainment: Senior Software Developer (2), Mid-Level Software Developer (3), Test Engineer (2), and Release Manager (1) (8 FTEs);
(c) Operations and Infrastructure: Systems Administrator (2), DevSecOps Engineer (2), and Database Administrator (1) (5 FTEs);
(d) Functional and User Support: Functional Analyst – HR (2), Training Specialist (1), and Tier III Help Desk Lead (1) (4 FTEs);
(e) Cybersecurity and Compliance: Information Systems Security Officer (ISSO) (1) (1 FTE).

The Contractor shall ensure that all 22 FTEs hold, or are eligible to obtain within 60 days of task order award, a favorable Common Access Card (CAC) credential and a minimum of a Secret security clearance (NACI/Tier 3). The Program Manager and ISSO shall hold current DoD 8570.01-M / DoD 8140 compliant certifications (e.g., PMP, CISSP). Staffing levels may be adjusted via bilateral modification per FAR 52.243-1 (Changes – Fixed Price). The Government will evaluate Offeror's proposed organizational chart and résumés under Technical Evaluation Factor 3 – Personnel Qualifications and Management Approach, as described in Section M.4.3.

52.219-14 Limitations on Subcontracting (Oct 2022)

(a) This clause does not apply to the unrestricted portion of a partial set-aside.
(b) Definition. Similarly situated entity, as used in this clause, means a first-tier subcontractor, including an independent contractor, that-
(1) Has the same small business program status as that which qualified the prime contractor for the award (e.g., for a small business set-aside contract, any small business concern, without regard to its socioeconomic status); and
(2) Is considered small for the size standard under the North American Industry Classification System (NAICS) code the prime contractor assigned to the subcontract.
(c) Applicability. This clause applies only to-
(1) Contracts that have been set aside for any of the small business concerns identified in 19.000(a)(3);
(2) Part or parts of a multiple-award contract that have been set aside for any of the small business concerns identified in 19.000(a)(3);
(3) Contracts that have been awarded on a sole-source basis in accordance with subparts 19.8, 19.13, 19.14, and 19.15;
(6) Contracts using the HUBZone price evaluation preference to award to a HUBZone small business concern unless the concern waived the evaluation preference.

Phase 2: Solution Presentation/Pitch

Down selected offerors will be invited to present their solutions to the Government and to participate in a live demonstration. The presentation shall include:

Detailed technical and business viability of the solution

Proposed schedule and milestones

Anticipated data rights assertions

Explanation of Data Rights

Rough Order of Magnitude (ROM) pricing: Estimated cost and payment terms.

7.2. Participation in the live demonstration in a relevant environment will be coordinated by the Government.

Phase 2: Presentation/Pitch Evaluation

Individual presentations/pitches will be evaluated against the evaluation criteria below and not against any other presentations/pitches. Presentation/pitch submissions will be valid for 120 days after pitch evaluation. The government will aim to complete evaluation of presentation/pitches within 30 calendar days of the presentation/pitch. After completing the evaluation of presentation/pitch submissions, the government will notify the company that: they may submit a Full Proposal for evaluation in Phase 3; or their proposed concept/technology/solution is not of continued interest to the Government, and they will not be required to submit a Full Proposal and advance to Phase 3.

Presentation/Pitch evaluation criteria are listed in order of importance from top to bottom. Presentation/pitches shall be evaluated/scored on the following factors:

Level of relevancy of the solution in addressing the A-COP with a commercially available product and/or process;

The technical merit of the proposed solution adequately addressed the A-COP and demonstrated feasibility for the Government to pursue the proposed solution;

Level of uniqueness, and/or innovative approach to solve the Government's need;

Level of technical risk/maturity;

Level of risk placed with the proposed ROM;

Level of risk in the proposed milestone schedule and its ability to meet the A-COP requirement within a relevant time period;

Level of risk in the company's viability and business solution; and

Level of potential risk in anticipated IP and data rights assertions

FACTOR 3 – Oral Presentation (Qualified Invited Offerors Only):
Evaluation:
The qualified offeror(s) who are invited to participate in MSU's Oral Presentation factor will be evaluated against the following key elements, ensuring a comprehensive and fair assessment:
1. Offeror's understanding of MSU's mission, operations, and organizational complexity structures;
2. Offeror's system functionality and technical demonstration;
3. Offeror's presentation effectiveness, including time management;
4. Offeror's implementation and support plan demonstration; and
5. Offeror's presentation on its team qualification and responsiveness

FACTOR 4 - Past Performance:
MSU will evaluate the offeror's past performance. Past performance information may consider predecessor companies, key personnel who have relevant experience or subcontractors that will perform major or critical aspects of the requirement. In the case of an offeror without a record of relevant past performance or for whom information on past performance is not available, the offeror may not be evaluated favorably or unfavorably.

3. Integrate with FEMA's Individual Assistance Processing System and IA Ecosystem
Provide integration patterns, APIs, connectors, or other mechanisms that allow insurance verification and data-sharing capabilities to be integrated with FEMA's Individual Assistance Processing System and associated IA systems and rules engines.
Support use cases such as:
• Automated checks for duplication of benefits;
• Automated or semi-automated underinsurance calculations;
• Caseworker decision support within Salesforce; and
• Audit trails and reporting for compliance and recoupment.

4.2 Integration with FEMA's Individual Assistance Processing System
a. Describe your experience and capabilities to integrate with Salesforce, including:
• Use of Salesforce APIs (REST, SOAP, Bulk, Streaming);
• Any existing Salesforce AppExchange apps, managed packages, or accelerators you offer;
• Experience with Salesforce Government Cloud or public sector implementations, if applicable.

SPECIFICATIONS & REQUIREMENTS

This scope of work for this project includes, but may not be limited to, the following information, drawings, technical specifications, and other attachments.

1. Service Provider must have and be able to demonstrate a minimum of <years> of successful experience completing the same or similar projects and/or scopes of work.
2. Service Provider will assign a competent project manager who has full authority to act for the Service Provider and who will be MCC's primary point of contact and coordination during the execution of the project.
3. Currently we have four exterior digital signs (outdoor video walls) and 100 or so traditional TVs across campus that need to connect to college information;
4. Solution must integrate with our Informacast system for emergency alerts and take over screens triggered by Informacast alerts to display emergency messaging on screens;
5. Selected vendor must provide a software-as-a-service platform that supports:
5.1. Hardware Agnostic Playback - integration with exciting TVs and/or external media players;
5.2. Centralized management - a single dashboard to control all screens regardless of physical location with the ability to display individual content based upon physical location;
5.3. Workflow efficiency - Create one, publish everywhere approach to distribution;
5.4. Ability to publish content from both external file sources or created from within the platform from a collection of customizable and editable templates. Templates must be branded to MCC;
5.5. Ability to power live streams and IPTV feeds in conjunction with the rest of the content being published to all devices;
5.6. Ability to offer role-based access and governance to create seamless workflows, allowing users to only see and do what they need to have access to see and do;
5.7. Ability to create approval workflows, so no content goes live until a publisher approves it;

